<section class="card">
  <h2>About Broccoli</h2>

  <p class="tagline">
    A cool-season crop that rewards early timing and steady growth.
  </p>

  <p class="lede">
    Broccoli performs best when it grows through cool spring temperatures. In a typical year at the 50% probability level (1991–2020 climate normals), your frost window sets the boundaries, but timing precision determines whether heads form before heat stress or late-season slowdown.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Quick Planning Reference</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Start indoors:</strong> ~6–8 weeks before transplant window</li>
    <li><strong>Transplant:</strong> near last frost to shortly after (depending on exposure)</li>
    <li><strong>Days to maturity:</strong> 55–90 days (variety-dependent)</li>
    <li><strong>Frost tolerance:</strong> Light (can tolerate light frost; hard cold slows growth)</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="fine muted">
    These are practical ranges. Growth interruptions (cold stall or heat spike) are the main drivers of “missed” timing.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Why Indoor Starts Matter</h2>

  <p>
    Broccoli usually performs best when started indoors and transplanted on schedule. Transplants help you:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Use early spring weeks when direct-sown seedlings would stall in cold soil</li>
    <li>Hold maturity inside the season boundary with more buffer</li>
    <li>Reduce the chance that head formation drifts into heat stress</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="fine">
    If you want the underlying model for “frost is a boundary, not a forecast,” see:
    <a href="/guides/average-frost-date-vs-actual-weather/">Average frost date vs actual weather</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Typical GDD Requirement</h2>

  <p><strong>Base temperature:</strong> 50°F (10°C) for heat-budget comparison</p>
  <p><strong>Approximate GDD needed:</strong> ~700–1,050 GDD (base 50) for many 55–90 day broccoli types</p>

  <p>
    Broccoli is cool-season, but maturity still depends on accumulated seasonal heat. In cooler summers, development slows and maturity can drift later, shrinking buffer before first frost.
  </p>

  <p class="fine muted" style="margin-top:14px;">
    GDD = ((Daily High + Daily Low) ÷ 2) − 50
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Use the GDD Planner</a>
  </div>

  <p class="fine">
    For the combined model, see:
    <a href="/guides/how-frost-dates-and-growing-degree-days-work-together/">How frost dates and Growing Degree Days work together</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Minimum Frost-Free Days</h2>

  <p>
    Many broccoli varieties need roughly <strong>55–90 days</strong> to reach harvest, depending on type and growing conditions.
    While broccoli tolerates light frost, growth rate and head quality decline as temperatures drop.
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Check Your Frost-Free Season</a>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Short-Season Viability Flag</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Good choice under 100 days?</strong> Often (especially with indoor starts and mid-early varieties)</li>
    <li><strong>Risky under 90 days?</strong> Can be, if transplant timing slips or heat spikes cause bolting</li>
    <li><strong>Needs season extension?</strong> Sometimes (row cover can preserve early growth and reduce wind stress)</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>First Frost Sensitivity</h2>

  <p>
    Broccoli tolerates light frost, but repeated freezes and hard cold slow growth and can degrade head quality.
    For frost-first modeling, treat 32°F (0°C) as the boundary and aim to mature heads with buffer ahead of that date.
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/first-frost-planner/">Plan Backward From First Frost</a>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Early-Maturing Strategy</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Start indoors so you can transplant on time and protect the early window</li>
    <li>Choose mid-early varieties when your frost window is tight</li>
    <li>Keep growth steady (avoid stalling from cold stress or drought)</li>
    <li>Use microclimates and light row cover to preserve growth rate</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Planning Model</h2>

  <p class="muted">
    Frost → Season Length → GDD → Crop Requirement → Risk Margin
  </p>

  <p>
    In a typical year, broccoli viability comes from matching variety maturity length to your frost window and maintaining enough heat accumulation to avoid delayed heading.
    When buffer is thin, timing slips are the main failure mode.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Model broccoli against the frost boundary at 32°F (0°C), using 50% probability climate normals.</li>
    <li>Maturity depends on steady time + heat accumulation, not just the calendar.</li>
    <li>Indoor starts improve buffer and reduce timing drift.</li>
    <li>Risk rises when delays push heading too close to first frost.</li>
  </ul>
</section>